{{Infobox musical artist | name = Fémina | background = group_or_band | image = File:F%C3%A9mina.jpg | landscape = | caption = Fémina in 2012 (from left to right: Sofía "Toti" Trucco, Clara Miglioli, and Clara "Wewi" Trucco) | origin = [[San Martín de los Andes]], Argentina | genre = {{flatlist| * Hip hop * Folk * Rap * Fusion }} | years_active = 2004-present | label = | website = {{URL|https://femina.bandcamp.com/}} | current_members = * Clara "Wewi" Trucco * Sofía "Toti" Trucco * Clara Miglioli }}
'''Fémina''' is an Argentine folk and fusion trio from [[San Martín de los Andes]], Argentina.
== Career == In 2004, friends Clara Miglioli and Sofía "Toti" Trucco formed Fémina in [[San Martín de los Andes]], Argentina.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com.ar/1351126-conoce-a-femina|title=Conocé a Fémina|last=Gallardo|first=Agustín|date=2011-02-18|work=Rolling Stone Argentina|access-date=2018-01-29|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=es}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.revistaohlala.com/1649214-bandas-de-chicas|title=Chicas en banda: ellas se animaron a su proyecto musical|last=Lascano|first=Catalina|date=|work=Revista Ohlalá|access-date=2018-01-30|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=es}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.indiehoy.com/descubrir/la-fusion-de-femina/|title=La fusión de Fémina|last=Ocampo|first=Loreta Neira|work=Indie Hoy|access-date=2018-01-30|language=es-MX}}</ref> The trio's name Fémina means female in [[Latin]].<ref name=":8">{{Cite news|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/07/paste-sessions-femina-defies-borders-with-three-ha.html|title=Fémina Defies Borders With Rap and Latin-Infused Tracks|last=Barr|first=Natalia|date=2017-07-14|work=Paste Magazine|access-date=2018-01-30|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en}}</ref> The trio chose the name because they liked its sound and message.<ref name=":8" /> Band member Toti elaborated "there were not too many female rappers. It was a way to represent our girl."<ref name=":8" /> Miglioli met the Trucco sisters when she was four years old.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.slobrew.com/2017/07/18/interview-clara-miglioli-femina/|title=Interview with Clara Miglioli of Fémina|last=|first=|date=2017-07-18|work=SLO Brew|access-date=2018-01-30|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en-US}}</ref> After completing high school, the duo moved to [[Buenos Aires]] at the age of 19.<ref name=":0" /> They were later joined by Toti's younger sister Clara "Wewi" Trucco on percussion.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=http://www.revistaaire.com/femina-potencia-ritmica-en-clave-femenina/|title=Fémina, potencia rítmica en clave femenina|last=Taylor|first=Moira|date=2017-02-02|work=Revista AIRE|access-date=2018-01-30|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=es-es}}</ref> There, they met and became friends with other rappers including [[Koxmoz]] and Apolo MC.<ref name=":4">{{Cite news|url=http://www.lavaca.org/mu74/rapear-sin-limites-femina/|title=Rapear sin límites: Fémina|last=|first=|date=2014-03-20|work=La Vaca|access-date=2018-01-30|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=es-LA}}</ref> In addition to music, both Miglioli and the Trucco sisters have a background in acting and vocal training.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://indianapublicmedia.org/arts/femina-urban-fusion-patagonia-universal-message/|title=Fémina: Urban Fusion From Patagonia With Universal Message|last=Boomershine|first=Hannah|date=2016-09-09|work=Indiana Public Media|access-date=2018-01-30|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> Fémina has toured in Latin America, Europe, and the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.labandaelastica.com/indie-corner/desde-argentina-femina-es-la-banda-de-la-semana-en-indiecorner#sthash.D9Tkf5iS.dpbs|title=Desde Argentina, Fémina es la banda de la semana en #IndieCorner|last=Jáuregui|first=Vicente|date=2016-10-18|work=La Banda Elastica|access-date=2018-01-30|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=es}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.efe.com/efe/usa/gente/femina-tres-musicas-argentinas-que-cruzan-lo-natural-y-la-urbe/50000102-3319614|title=Fémina, tres músicas argentinas que cruzan "lo natural y la urbe"|last=|first=|date=2017-07-07|work=EFE|access-date=2018-01-30|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=es-LA}}</ref> In 2018, they performed at the [[Sydney Festival]] in Australia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://themusic.com.au/music/livereviews/2018/01/23/femina-sydney-festival-magic-mirrors-spiegeltent-mj-oneill/|title=Femina (Sydney Festival)|last=O'Neill|first=MJ|date=2018-01-21|website=theMusic|language=en-GB|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-01-30}}</ref> In an August 2017 interview with the [[Rolling Stone]] magazine, the group announced they are working on a new album with producer [[Will Holland]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.indiehoy.com/especiales/entrevistas/femina-honor-una-voz-la-posibilidad-representar-muchas-mujeres/|title=Fémina: “Es un honor tener una voz y la posibilidad de representar a muchas mujeres”|last=Piterman|first=Juan|date=2018-01-31|work=Indie Hoy|access-date=2018-02-08|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=es-MX}}</ref><ref name=":5">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/10-new-artists-you-need-to-know-august-2017-w498043/fmina-w498053|title=10 New Artists You Need to Know Now|last=|first=|date=2017-08-17|website=Rolling Stone|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.miami.com/things-to-do-in-miami/an-argentinian-trio-wants-to-bring-the-world-together-now-theyre-bringing-their-message-to-miami-163824/|title=An Argentinian trio wants to bring the world together. Now they're bringing their message to Miami|last=Prism Creative Group|first=|date=2017-06-14|work=Miami|access-date=2018-01-31|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en-US}}</ref> Several tracks will feature [[Iggy Pop]].<ref name=":5" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.diarioregistrado.com/no-se/el-grupo-argentino-que-conquisto-el-oido-de-iggy-pop_a5926fd8fd669e67b19cf33c1|title=El grupo argentino que conquistó el oído de Iggy Pop|last=Gallo|first=Rodrigo|date=2017-05-25|work=Diario Registrado|access-date=2018-01-30|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=es-LA}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://rollingstoneaus.com/music/post/future-is-now-femina/7376|title=Future Is Now: Fémina|last=Raygoza|first=Isabela|date=2017-11-01|work=Rolling Stone Australia|access-date=2018-01-30|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref>
== Artistry == Their music often comprises harmonies and poetic rap in Spanish.<ref name=":1" /> Themes of their songs typically incorporate folklore, feminism, and Patagonia with an urban twist.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mtres.co/femina-el-power-trio-que-mezcla-el-folclor-con-la-magia-patagonica-y-el-sonido-urbano/|title=Fémina: El power trío que mezcla el folclor con la magia patagónica y el sonido urbano|last=Cortés|first=Julián López|date=2016-10-31|work=MTres|access-date=2018-01-30|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=es-ES}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.lostateminor.com/2017/12/22/talented-trio-behind-femina-talk-us-journey-argentinian-village-global-headlines/|title=The talented trio behind Fémina talk us through their journey from an Argentinian village to global headlines|last=MC|first=Jack|date=2017-12-22|work=Lost At E Minor|access-date=2018-01-30|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en-US}}</ref> In addition, messages of gender inequality, love, and unity can be found throughout their tracks.<ref name=":6">{{Cite web|url=https://www.univision.com/univision-news/culture/this-all-girl-argentine-trio-can-rap-sing-and-play-the-cajon|title=This all-girl Argentine trio can rap, sing and play the cajón|last=Martinez|first=Nicole|date=2016-09-12|website=Univision|language=es|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-01-30}}</ref> They were influenced by many artists including [[Clarice Lispector]], [[Fernando Pessoa]], [[The Roots]], [[Pete Rock]], [[Cypress Hill]], and [[Lauryn Hill]].<ref name=":4" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/how-femina-went-from-patagonia-to-mofo-via-iggy-pops-garden-20171204-gzyh4i.html|title=How Femina went from Patagonia to MOFO, via Iggy Pop's garden|last=Dwyer|first=Michael|date=2017-12-08|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=2018-01-31|language=en-US}}</ref>
== Members ==
=== Sofía "Toti" Trucco === Toti is {{Age as of date|32|2016|September|12}} years old and was raised in [[San Martín de los Andes]].<ref name=":6" /> After graduating from high school, she moved to [[Buenos Aires]].<ref name=":0" /> Like her younger sister, Wewi, Toti is also a percussionist. She frequently incorporates flamenco [[cajón]] in their music.<ref name=":1" /> Toti is also a dancer.<ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=http://mybeautifulair.com/2015/10/28/meet-the-talented-trio-behind-femina/|title=Meet the Talented Trio Behind Fémina|last=Portillo|first=Grace|date=2015-10-28|work=Buenos Aires Arts & Lifestyle {{!}} My Beautiful Air|access-date=2018-01-30|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=}}</ref> She is working on a project with Luis Maurette and is enrolled in a hip hop history and dance classes.<ref name=":3" /> Outside of Fémina, Toti performs in the Buenos Aires [[Underground music|underground]] as Sof Tot. She recorded an unreleased EP with Uji who also goes by Luis Maurette of the band [[Lulacruza]].<ref name=":7" />
=== Clara Miglioli === Miglioli is {{Age as of date|32|2016|September|12}} years old and was raised in [[San Martín de los Andes]].<ref name=":6" /> Growing up in Patagonia, Miglioli learned about hip hop through watching video cassettes of MTV.<ref name=":4" /> She enjoyed lisining to [[Tupac Shakur]] and [[Cypress Hill]].<ref name=":4" /> At the age of 19, Miglioli moved to Bueno Aires where she studied with actor {{ill|Pompeyo Audivert|es}} who inspired her to write.<ref name=":4" /> She wrote poetry in addition to her participation in the band.<ref name=":0" /> Miglioli is the primary vocalist of Fémina.<ref name=":1" /> Outside of Fémina, Miglioli releases music under the name Claridad.<ref name=":7" /> She independently released a rap fusion solo album titled ''Sublime''.<ref name=":3" /><ref name=":7">{{Cite news|url=https://soundsandcolours.com/articles/argentina/femina-unexpected-connection-magic-patagonian-mountains-hip-hop-iggy-pop-37946/|title=Fémina and the Unexpected Connections Between Patagonia's Magical Mountains, Hip-Hop and Iggy Pop|last=Data|first=Juan|date=2017-08-30|work=Sounds and Colours|access-date=2018-01-30|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en-GB}}</ref> Together with her brother, Oli Miglioli, Clara formed the band Hermandad.<ref name=":7" />
=== Clara "Wewi" Trucco === Wewi is {{Age as of date|25|2016|September|12}} years old and was raised in [[San Martín de los Andes]].<ref name=":6" /> She is the younger sister of Toti and the newest member of Fémina. Self described as a percussionist, Wewi plays the guitar and the Bolivian [[Charango|ronroco]].<ref name=":1" /> She is also a visual artist and illustrator, who, at first, moved to Buenos Aires to pursue a career in the arts.<ref name=":6" /><ref name=":3" /> Outside of Fémina, Wewi formed Weste, an indie folk band composed of herself and Uruguayan musician Igna Pérez.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pagina12.com.ar/52545-por-mas-que-cada-uno-haga-la-suya-somos-una-gran-crew|title=Por más que cada uno haga la suya, somos una gran crew|last=Rojas|first=Yumber Vera|date=2017-07-27|work=Página 12|access-date=2018-01-30|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=es-AR}}</ref> They released their debut album ''Visceras'' featuring a mixture of folk-rap and indie pop.<ref name=":3" /><ref name=":7" />
