{{Expand German|Götz Puppenmanufaktur|date=July 2017}} {{refimprove|date=July 2017}} {{Infobox company | name = Götz Puppenmanufaktur | logo = File:Gotz Puppenmanufaktur logo.png | type = [[Gesellschaft mit beschränkter Haftung]] | traded_as = Götz | foundation = {{start date|1950}} in Rödental, Germany | founder = Marianne and Franz Götz | location = Rödental, Germany | area_served = Worldwide | industry = [[Toy]]s | products = [[Doll]]s and related toys | num_employees = | revenue = | subsid = | homepage = {{URL|http://www.goetz-puppen.de}} }} '''Götz Puppenmanufaktur International'''{{efn|The [[ö]] is a German [[umlaut (linguistics)|umlaut]]. In case this letter is not available, it may be written as oe (e.g. in the company's homepage name www.goetz-puppen.de). In some cases the dots are simply ignored. Therefore one might as well find Goetz or Gotz instead of Götz in the references.}} GmbH is a German doll manufacturer, founded in [[Rödental]], [[Germany]], in 1950.
The company was founded in 1950 by Marianne and Franz Götz. Götz's first dolls were handmade of [[papier-mâché]] by family members and sold directly by Franz Götz<ref name="van Patten">{{cite web|url=https://www.thespruce.com/gotz-dolls-overview-4083331|title=What You Need To Know About Götz Dolls|last=van Patten|first=Denise|work=The Spruce|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref> until 1957, when they switched to producing dolls using [[rotational molding]]. The company is also known among collectors for designing and manufacturing the first [[American Girl]] dolls–[[Kirsten Larson]], [[Samantha Parkington]] and [[Molly McIntire]]–for Pleasant Company during the 1980s to 1990s, the face mold being based off an existing doll from Götz.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Falligant|first1=Erin|last2=Calkhoven|first2=Laurie|last3=Anton|first3=Carrie|others=Tripp, Valerie|title=American Girl: Ultimate Visual Guide|url=https://www.amazon.com/American-Girl-Ultimate-Visual-Guide/dp/1465444963|date=6 September 2016|publisher=[[Dorling Kindersley|DK Children]]|isbn=1465444963}}</ref>
