{{Infobox building | name = Sesshū Memorial Museum | native_name = 益田市立雪舟の郷記念館 | image = Masuda Kanetaka by Sesshu.jpg | caption = Portrait of Masuda Kanetaka by [[Sesshū]] ([[Important Cultural Properties of Japan|ICP]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bunka.go.jp/bsys/maindetails.asp?register_id=201&item_id=1045 |script-title=ja:紙本著色益田兼尭像〈雪舟ノ印アリ／〉 |trans-title=Portrait of Masuda Kanetaka, colour on paper, with Sesshu's seal |language=Japanese |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=27 February 2016}}</ref> | cost = | owner = | address = 1149 Otoyoshi-chō | location_town = [[Masuda, Shimane|Masuda]], [[Shimane Prefecture]] | location_country = [[Japan]] | coordinates = {{coord|34.68503753|N|131.84752697|E|display=title,inline|format=dms|type:landmark_region:JP_scale:10000}} | opened_date = October 1990 | inauguration_date = | renovation_date = | demolition_date = | destruction_date = | other_dimensions = | floor_count = | floor_area = | architect = | architecture_firm = | url = {{homepage|http://www.iwami.or.jp/sessyu3/index.htm}} }}
{{nihongo|'''Sesshū Memorial Museum'''|益田市立雪舟の郷記念館|Masuda Shiritsu Sesshū no Sato Kinenkan}} opened in [[Masuda, Shimane|Masuda]], [[Shimane Prefecture]], Japan, in 1990. Located next to the site of the {{nihongo|Daiki-an|大喜庵}}, said to have been the site of [[Sesshū]]'s death and burial, the museum stages exhibitions relating to the artist and to the history of Masuda.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iwami.or.jp/sessyu3/1_kinenkan/aramashi/aramashi.htm |script-title=ja:記念館について |trans-title=About the Museum |language=Japanese |publisher=Iwami Internet |accessdate=27 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.city.masuda.lg.jp/kanko/sessyu_03.html |script-title=ja:雪舟の郷記念館 |trans-title=Sesshu Memorial Museum |language=Japanese |publisher=[[Masuda, Shimane|Masuda City]] |accessdate=27 February 2016}}</ref> The collection includes one [[Important Cultural Properties of Japan|Important Cultural Property]], Sesshū's 1479 portrait of {{nihongo|[[Masuda Kanetaka]]|[[:ja:益田兼堯|益田兼堯]]}}; two [[Cultural Properties of Japan|Prefectural Cultural Properties]], {{nihongo|Yasutomi Family Documents|安富家文書}} and {{nihongo|Sufu Family Documents|周布家文書}}; and seven [[Cultural Properties of Japan|Municipal Cultural Properties]], three scrolls with flowers and birds attributed to Sesshū, a pair of landscape [[byōbu]] by {{nihongo|[[Unkoku Tōeki]]|[[:ja:雲谷等益|雲谷等益]]}}, [[Bodhidharma|Daruma]], Ikuzanshu, and Seiōgyū by the same painter, sailing boats in an autumn bay and travel through snow-covered mountains by the same artist, lotus and heron by {{nihongo|Saitō Tōshitsu|斎藤等室筆}}, [[Bodhidharma|Daruma]] by {{nihongo|Unkoku Tōoku|雲谷等屋}}, and {{nihongo|Yoshida Family Documents|吉田家文書}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.city.masuda.lg.jp/soshiki/51/detail-1552.html |script-title=ja:益田市指定文化財件数一覧 |trans-title=Number of Cultural Properties in Masuda City |language=Japanese |publisher=[[Masuda, Shimane|Masuda City]] |accessdate=27 February 2016}}</ref>
